channel.title: Insects and other Invertebrates of Riddells Creek
channel.description: This is for all the other insects and other invertebrates that occur in Riddells Creek. Note that there are other collections for specific groups including Butterflies, Moths, Grasshoppers, Dragonflies, Spiders.

item.title: Diuris punctata, Lasioglossum (Chilalictus) spp.

item.description: Small native bee pollinator of the threatened and vulnerable Purple Diuris.

item.title: Commius elegans

item.title: Omorgus australasiae

item.title: Netelia spp.
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: About half the size of the other common, large red Netelia wasp seen at this location. ID as Netelia spp. by Ken Walker who is also not sure it is Netelia spp.. Ken added "There are several genera (eg: Enicophilus, Ophion, Leptophion, Riekophion etc) that all have the same body shape and colour. The wing venation is the key to distinguishing these genera. I have punted for Netelia as and identification because I believe I can see a small triangular cell on the outer margins of the forewings."

item.title: Ichneumonidae spp.
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: White 'spectacles'. White socks on rear legs. White bands on antennae. In open woodland. Exhibited hunting wasp behaviour (short low flights, antennae monitoring ground activity). Same species as 12494. Very small.

item.title: Eurygryllodes spp.

item.description: I suspect this is the whistling Cricket that can be heard every night giving a lovely soft whistle. Whistles at 5200Hz which is picked up by an iPhone but not by my Samsung phone!

item.title: Diamma bicolor
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Despite the name it is a parasitic wasp. Females are wingless & often seen wandering on the ground looking for mole crickets. They lay an egg on the paralysed cricket, with the cricket then being used as food for the developing wasp larva.

item.title: Cryptocheilus bicolor

item.title: Tiphiidae spp.
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Female is wingless. Adults feed on nectar. Female burrows into the ground, parasitising beetle larvae & mole crickets. They are important pollinators of native plants. Females sometimes mistaken for ants. (adapted from ABC website)
